74 THE ODES OF HORACE

Greed, sels-indulgent, like the dropsy, grows, Its thirst unslakod ; and while the cause remains Of dire disease, nor flies the poisoned veins, Through the pale {rame the watery languor flows.

Phraates to the throne of Persian kings Restored —- dissenting Virtue strikes his name From those deemed happy by the world's acchim, Unteaching the false names men give to things.

The diadem and a sure empire bring, And deathless bays -- to him who passos by Huge heaps of gold, and with no longing eye Looks back upon them ,- —— he alone is king.
